n the Inland Northwest / rJaniewski, Dolores -- tPART III. CONTRADICTIONS OF SOCIAL WELFARE -- t11. Women in the Public Sphere in Early Modern England: The Case of the Urban Working Poor / rWillen, Diane -- t12. Good and Bad Mothers: Lady Philanthropists and London Housewives before World War I / rRoss, Ellen -- t13. Federal Help for Mothers: The Rise and Fall of the Sheppard-Towner Act in the I920s / rLadd-Taylor, Molly -- t14. A Right Not to Be Beaten: The Agency of Battered Women, 1880-I96o / rGordon, Linda -- t15. The Black Community and the Birth Control Movement / rRodrique, Jessie M. -- tPART IV. LINKED LIVES: THE WORLDS OF GENDER, WORK, AND FAMILY -- t16. The Just Price, the Free Market, and the Value of Women / rKessler-Harris, Alice -- t17. The Masculinization of Production: The Gendering of Work and Skill in U.S. Newspaper Printing, 1850-1920 / rBaron, Ava -- t18. Between Taylorism and Denatalite: Women Welfare Supervisors and the Boundaries of Difference in French Metalworking Factories, 1917-I930 / rLee Downs, Laura -- t19. Family, Work, and Community: Southern and Eastern European Immigrant Women Speak from the Connecticut Federal Writers' Project / rAnker, Laura -- t20. Sexism by a Subtler Name?: Postindustrial Conditions and Postfeminist Consciousness in the Silicon Valley / rStacey, Judith -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over two centuries the notion that societies have been sharply divided into women's (private) and men's (public) spheres has been used both to describe and to prescribe social life. More recently, it has been applied and critiqued by feminist scholars as an explanation for women's oppression. Spanning a rich array of historical contexts-from medieval nunneries to Ottoman harems to Paris communes to electronics firms in today's Silicon Valley-the twenty essays collected here offer a pathbreaking reassessment of the significance of the concept of separate spheres.After a theoretical introduction by the editors, certain essays reexamine historians' definitions of public and private realms and show how the imposition of these categories often obscures the realities of power structures and the alterable nature of gender roles. Other chapters consider how the concept of separate domains has been used to control women's actions. Additional essays explore the limits of public/private distinctions, focusing on women's working lives, the role of the state in the family, and the ways in which women including Native North Americans, African-Americans in the birth control movement, and participants in the lesbian bar culture have themselves reshaped the model of separate spheres.Making available the best papers on the public/private theme delivered at the 1987 Berkshire Conference on the History of Women, Gendered Domains will be welcomed by anyone interested in women's studies, including historians, political scientists, feminist theorists, anthropologists, sociologists, and philosophers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aWomen in public lifexHistoryvCongresses. 0aWomenxHistoryvCongresses. 4aWomens Studies. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh1 aHelly, Dorothy O., eeditor.1 aReverby, Susan M., eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501720741423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501720741.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  